	<article class="post-54555 post type-post status-publish hentry category-caribbean-oceans category-coral-biology category-economics category-endangered-species category-environmental-policy category-industry category-oceans tag-antigua-and-barbuda tag-caribbean-area tag-coral tag-curacao tag-documentary-films-and-programs tag-environment tag-fish-and-other-marine-life tag-montserrat tag-oceans-and-seas tag-olson-randy tag-pace-university tag-reefs tag-sustainable-living per-olson-randy des-coral des-documentary-films-and-programs des-environment des-fish-and-other-marine-life des-oceans-and-seas des-reefs des-sustainable-living org-pace-university geo-antigua-and-barbuda geo-caribbean-area geo-curacao geo-montserrat news_keywords-antigua-and-barbuda news_keywords-caribbean-2 news_keywords-coral news_keywords-curacao news_keywords-documentaries news_keywords-environment news_keywords-fish-2 news_keywords-montserrat news_keywords-oceans-and-seas news_keywords-pace-university news_keywords-randy-olson-2 news_keywords-reef news_keywords-sustainable-living-2" id="post-54555">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/category/oceans/?module=BlogCategory&version=Blog Post&action=Click&contentCollection=Opinion&pgtype=Blogs&region=Header">oceans</a></span>
		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">By Land and Sea, Cura&ccedil;ao Seeks to Sustain Its Coral Bounty</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Andrew C. Revkin			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-03-20T19:45:22+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">March 20, 2015 3:45 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">March 20, 2015 3:45 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/20/underwater-and-on-land-curaao-seeks-to-sustain-its-coral-bounty/" data-title="By Land and Sea, Cura&ccedil;ao Seeks to Sustain Its Coral Bounty" data-description="Young filmmakers examine efforts on CuraÃ§ao to sustain the island&#039;s coral bounty while enhancing its economy.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaofilming/dotcuracaofilming-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaofilming/dotcuracaofilming-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaofilming/dotcuracaofilming-blog480.jpg" id="100000003584255" width="480" height="320" alt="Pace University students filming a documentary on coral conservation in CuraÃ§ao shielded their camera from the rain during a brief downpour."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Pace University students filming a documentary on coral conservation in CuraÃ§ao shielded their camera from the rain during a brief downpour.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrew C. Revkin</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly><span id="t0h2s" class="update">Updated, 12:02 a.m., March 21 | </span></webonly><br />
WILLEMSTAD, CuraÃ§ao &#8212; I apologize for the prolonged blog silence (I have withdrawal symptoms!), but this week has been devoted to filming, not writing. Since my <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/12/21/my-second-half/">move to Pace University five years ago</a>, I&#8217;ve been working each spring with a colleague, <a href="//www.pace.edu/faculty/maria-luskay-edd">Prof. Maria Luskay</a>, to focus a long-running documentary production course on environmental stories.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This year&#8217;s film, &#8220;CuraÃ§aoâs Coral Challenge â Reviving the Rain Forests of the Sea,&#8221; will be the third to explore humanity&#8217;s evolving relationship with the oceans (along with our <a title="sea turtle conservation film" href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/05/08/can-technology-and-tourism-sustain-mexicos-sea-turtles/">sea turtle</a> and <a title="farming shrimp while limiting environmental impacts" href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/05/14/farming-shrimp-with-the-planet-in-mind/">shrimp farming</a> films).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As with all of ourÂ previousÂ films, this one (coming in mid May) will center on a society seeking toÂ enhance its economy without diminishing its environmental patrimony. In CuraÃ§ao&#8217;s case, the challenge is finding ways to move beyond an economy <a title="oil and Curacao's economy" href="//caribya.com/curacao/economy/">based for nearly 100 years on refining Venezuelan oil</a> to a more diverse one including substantial tourism &#8212; but doing so without degrading the still-vibrant reefs ringing parts of its coast.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaooil/dotcuracaooil-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaooil/dotcuracaooil-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaooil/dotcuracaooil-blog480.jpg" id="100000003584490" width="480" height="262" alt="For nearly 100 years, CuraÃ§ao&#039;s economy has centered on exports of refined Venezuelan oil."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="262"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">For nearly 100 years, CuraÃ§ao's economy has centered on exports of refined Venezuelan oil.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrew C. Revkin</span></figcaption></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaokeys/dotcuracaokeys-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaokeys/dotcuracaokeys-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaokeys/dotcuracaokeys-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003584311" width="190" height="276" alt="A coral disease spread across the Caribbean in the 1970s, wiping out 95 percent of elkhorn and staghorn populations. Photographs show the impact onÂ Carysfort Reef in the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary from 1975 to 2004."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="276"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A coral disease spread across the Caribbean in the 1970s, wiping out 95 percent of elkhorn and staghorn populations. Photographs show the impact onÂ Carysfort Reef in the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary from 1975 to 2004.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Phillip Dustan/IUCN</span></figcaption></figure></div></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many reefs across the Caribbean,* right up to the Florida Keys, have been <a href="//cmsdata.iucn.org/downloads/executive_summary_caribbean_status_report_eng.pdf">devastated since the 1970s</a> by a series of assaults from introduced diseases of Acropora coral (elkhorn and staghorn) and sea urchins (which help keep algae at bay), compounded by flows of pollution and overfishing accompanying rapid development.*Â <a href="//thedianerehmshow.org/shows/2014-08-05/environmental-outlook-health-and-future-our-coral-reefs">Climate change poses a growing threat</a>, with dropping ocean pH adding another stress. (And then there are introduced lionfish, <a title="Lionfish sashimi in Curacao" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9TpUEHEVu8c">which &#8212; happily &#8212; we saw turned into sashimi</a>.)</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaofisherman/dotcuracaofisherman-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaofisherman/dotcuracaofisherman-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotcuracaofisherman/dotcuracaofisherman-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003584231" width="190" height="113" alt="Edwin âMakambiâ Flameling, a commercial fisherman inÂ CuraÃ§ao, is against intensive coastal development, like the homes behind him, but also dislikes talk of no-fishing zones."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="113"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Edwin âMakambiâ Flameling, a commercial fisherman inÂ CuraÃ§ao, is against intensive coastal development, like the homes behind him, but also dislikes talk of no-fishing zones.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrew C. Revkin</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But, <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/04/protecting-parrotfish-on-the-path-to-a-caribbean-reef-revival/">as I reported last yea</a>r, there&#8217;s plenty that can be done to limit losses and, in some cases, boost prospects that Caribbean reefs will be around for a very long time to come. AndÂ CuraÃ§ao is a rare exception, with <a href="//repeatingislands.com/2013/07/07/curacaos-oostpunt-reef-among-the-best-in-the-caribbean/">extraordinary reefs on its east end</a> (<a href="//www.agrra.org/ARB_volume/Curacao%20Fish4-27-03.pdf">Oostpunt</a>) and north shore.*</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last month, CuraÃ§ao, along with Montserrat, <a href="//voices.nationalgeographic.com/2015/02/26/blue-halo-initiative-expands-to-montserrat-and-curacao/">signed an agreement with the Waitt Institute</a>, a group devoted to &#8220;using the ocean without using itÂ up,&#8221; to develop a marineÂ managementÂ plan that is both politically viable and environmentally sound. This is no easy task, in large part because limiting impacts on reefs is as much about managing activitiesÂ on land, the main source of pollution, as it is about managing activities on the water.<span id="more-54555"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The institute is led by <a title="Ayana Elizabeth Johnson" href="//ayanaelizabeth.com/about/bio/">Ayana Elizabeth Johnson</a>, a young marine biologist with Caribbean roots and a passion for policy. She&#8217;ll be featured in our film, along with <a href="//www.parlamento.cw/members/154/">Glenn Sulvaran</a>, a member of parliament with a passion for reef conservation, and <a href="https://lightscameracoral.wordpress.com/2015/03/20/tourism-development-and-sustainability-three-sides-of-curacao/">Faisal Dilrosun</a>, a government health and environment advisor.<!--more--></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The first such &#8220;<a title="Blue Halo plan for Barbuda" href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/22/a-small-island-takes-a-big-step-on-ocean-conservation/">Blue Halo</a>&#8221; initiative was launchedÂ in Barbuda in 2012 and recently produced pioneeringÂ <a href="//bit.ly/ngblog19" target="_blank">ocean zoning</a>Â legislation there.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/paceelkhorn/paceelkhorn-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/paceelkhorn/paceelkhorn-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/paceelkhorn/paceelkhorn-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003584034" width="190" height="126" alt="One-year-old colonies of endangered elkhorn coral grown in an aquarium were cemented to boulders along the Curacao coast in August, 2012."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="126"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">One-year-old colonies of endangered elkhorn coral grown in an aquarium were cemented to boulders along the Curacao coast in August, 2012.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Paul Selvaggio/Secore.org</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The film will also describeÂ a <a title="coral propagation project in Curacao" href="//www.secore.org/site/our-work/detail/project-curacao.2.html">coral propagation effort</a> pursued by the <a href="//www.secore.org/site/">Secore Foundation</a>, <a href="//www.carmabi.org/">Carmabi Foundation</a> and CuraÃ§ao Sea Aquarium &#8212; in particular the work of ValÃ©rie F. Chamberland, a biologist who has spent nearly five years cultivating extremely endangered elkhorn coral in tanks and cementing them on boulders just offshore. The oldest batch, &#8220;planted&#8221;Â two and a half years ago, is poised, if all goes well, to produce its own spawn in August, Chamberland told us.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotelkhorn15/dotelkhorn15-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotelkhorn15/dotelkhorn15-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotelkhorn15/dotelkhorn15-blog480.jpg" id="100000003584050" width="480" height="307" alt="ValÃ©rie F. Chamberland, a marine biologist, examines a colony of endangered elkhorn coral growing on a breakwater in CuraÃ§aoÂ three and a half years after she and others cultivated it from spawn in a Secore Foundation research project."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="307"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">ValÃ©rie F. Chamberland, a marine biologist, examines a colony of endangered elkhorn coral growing on a breakwater in CuraÃ§aoÂ three and a half years after she and others cultivated it from spawn in a Secore Foundation research project.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrew C. Revkin</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You can learn more about ways scientists have found to encourage coral spawning from Kristen Marhaver, a biologist based at the Carmabi research institute here but who was away at this year&#8217;s <a href="https://conferences.ted.com/TED2015/">TED conference</a> while we were filming. Her <a href="//ideas.ted.com/a-day-in-the-life-of-baby-coral/">TED slides are here</a> and <a href="//www.npr.org/2015/03/19/393586215/scientists-catch-up-on-the-sex-life-of-coral-to-help-reefs-survive">NPR just covered her work on the sex life of endangered pillar corals.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We arrived in CuraÃ§ao last Saturday and leave tomorrow with hard drives jammed with gigabytes of interviews and images of tropical fish and untreated sewage, pristine and overbuilt coastlines, coral nurseries and oil rigs, divers and fishermen (some of whom question the need for no-fishing zones) and much more.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You can read daily posts from <a href="https://www.facebook.com/jhennifer.moises">Jhennifer Moises Dos Santos</a> on the film project on the students&#8217; blog, &#8220;<a href="//lightscameracoral.wordpress.com">Lights, Cameras, Coral.</a>&#8221; And don&#8217;t miss <a href="https://www.facebook.com/cassie.pacenka?fref=ts">Cassie Pacenka</a>&#8216;s daily &#8220;vlog&#8221; (video blog)!</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Today&#8217;s video has a fun moment when Ayana Johnson meets a parrotfish during our interview:</p>
<div class="w480">
<div class="w480 youtube-video-container">
<div class="youtube-video" data-youtube-id="6M2ZUKPFZJA" data-start="">
<div class="thumb"><img src="https://img.youtube.com/vi/6M2ZUKPFZJA/0.jpg" />
<div class="playButton">
<div class="arrow"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We will distill all of this down to a tight 20 minutes, hopefully adhering to Randy Olson&#8217;s &#8220;and, but, therefore&#8221; story-structure mantra (<a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/09/09/can-storytelling-be-factual-and-effective/">you&#8217;re telling a story any time you replace an &#8220;and&#8221; with a &#8220;but&#8221; or &#8220;therefore&#8221;</a>).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We&#8217;ll describe many challenges facing those seeking to sustain the environment in the face of development pressures, but my sense is that we&#8217;ll end on an optimistic note given the energy and determination of the people we&#8217;ve met, including <a href="https://www.facebook.com/rdejongh?fref=ts">Ryan De Jongh</a>, who not only leads kayak tours but has spent years, on his own time, planting and propagating mangrove seedlings along shores denuded in the past.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotmangroveproject/dotmangroveproject-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotmangroveproject/dotmangroveproject-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/20/blogs/dotmangroveproject/dotmangroveproject-blog480.jpg" id="100000003584081" width="480" height="255" alt="In a CuraÃ§aoÂ bay, a student filmmaking team from Pace University kayaks past a mangrove propagation project run by Ryan De Jongh, an ecotourism guide and environmentalist."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="255"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">In a CuraÃ§aoÂ bay, a student filmmaking team from Pace University kayaks past a mangrove propagation project run by Ryan De Jongh, an ecotourism guide and environmentalist.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrew C. Revkin</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Postscript,</em> 12:01 a.m., March 21 | * <em>I&#8217;ve adjusted language at the asterisks to better reflect the condition of reefs in various parts of the Caribbean.</em></p>
	</div>
